1️⃣ What is a Service Object?

A service object is just a plain Ruby class that:

Encapsulates business logic outside models/controllers.

Example in Rails:

app/services/payment_processor.rb
2️⃣ Simple Service Example

Let’s build one.

Requirement:

Deduct amount from user balance

Raise error if insufficient balance

Send notification email

Service Code
class PaymentProcessor
  def initialize(user)
    @user = user
  end

  def call(amount)
    raise "Insufficient balance" if @user.balance < amount

    @user.update!(balance: @user.balance - amount)
    NotificationService.send_email(@user)

    true
  end
end
3️⃣ Basic RSpec Structure

Create file:

spec/services/payment_processor_spec.rb

Basic structure:

require "rails_helper"

RSpec.describe PaymentProcessor do
  describe "#call" do
    # tests go here
  end
end
4️⃣ Testing Success Case (State Change)
RSpec.describe PaymentProcessor do
  describe "#call" do
    let(:user) { User.create!(balance: 100) }

    it "deducts the amount from balance" do
      processor = described_class.new(user)

      processor.call(50)

      expect(user.reload.balance).to eq(50)
    end
  end
end
🔥 Important

We used:

expect(user.reload.balance).to eq(50)

This is state-based testing.

We verify DB change.

5️⃣ Testing Failure Case (Exception)
it "raises error if insufficient balance" do
  user.update!(balance: 20)

  processor = described_class.new(user)

  expect {
    processor.call(50)
  }.to raise_error("Insufficient balance")
end

Now we’re testing error handling.

6️⃣ Testing Side Effects (change matcher — very important)

Better version:

it "reduces user balance" do
  processor = described_class.new(user)

  expect {
    processor.call(50)
  }.to change { user.reload.balance }.from(100).to(50)
end

This is cleaner.

Interviewers love this.

7️⃣ Now Important: External Dependency

Service calls:

NotificationService.send_email(@user)

We do NOT want real emails in test.

So we stub it.

Stub Example
it "sends notification email" do
  allow(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)

  processor = described_class.new(user)
  processor.call(50)

  expect(NotificationService).to have_received(:send_email).with(user)
end

This is spy-style verification.

8️⃣ Cleaner Pattern (Arrange–Act–Assert)

Better structured version:

it "sends notification email" do
  # Arrange
  allow(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)

  # Act
  described_class.new(user).call(50)

  # Assert
  expect(NotificationService)
    .to have_received(:send_email)
    .with(user)
end

This is clean and readable.

9️⃣ When To Use Stub vs Mock in Services
Use Stub:

When dependency return value matters.

Example:

allow(Gateway).to receive(:charge).and_return(true)
Use Spy:

When you just verify interaction happened.

allow(Service).to receive(:call)
expect(Service).to have_received(:call)
Use Mock:

When interaction is critical and must happen.

expect(Service).to receive(:call)

But spies are generally preferred.

🔟 Full Professional-Level Spec

Clean production-style test:

RSpec.describe PaymentProcessor do
  describe "#call" do
    let(:user) { User.create!(balance: 100) }

    before do
      allow(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)
    end

    context "when balance is sufficient" do
      it "reduces balance" do
        expect {
          described_class.new(user).call(50)
        }.to change { user.reload.balance }.by(-50)
      end

      it "sends notification email" do
        described_class.new(user).call(50)

        expect(NotificationService)
          .to have_received(:send_email)
          .with(user)
      end
    end

    context "when balance is insufficient" do
      it "raises error" do
        expect {
          described_class.new(user).call(200)
        }.to raise_error("Insufficient balance")
      end
    end
  end
end

This is solid.

🧠 How To Think When Writing Service Specs

Always test:

Return value (if meaningful)

State change

External interactions

Error cases

Edge cases

🎯 Interview-Ready Answer

If interviewer asks:

“How do you test service objects in RSpec?”

You say:

I test service objects by verifying state changes using the change matcher, testing error conditions with raise_error, and stubbing external dependencies using allow(...).to receive to isolate business logic. I also verify important interactions using have_received when necessary.

That’s a senior-level answer.

